The group is believed to be part of a syndicate that was allegedly working with Home Affairs officials to fraudulently issue South African passports to foreign nationals at a cost of R40 000 ($2 700). Last week, South Africa’s Home Affairs Minister, Aaron Motsoaledi, said the syndicate’s kingpin was working with corrupt officials in his department in a network that spanned Gauteng, Limpopo, KwaZulu-Natal, Eastern Cape, Western Cape and Mpumalanga provinces. Horisani Sithole reports… --SABC--